BISD Food Services Update during COVID-19
Wednesday, 08/19/20

For the safety of all students, no parents/visitors during lunch, until further notice. Additionally, meals may not be delivered during the school day by the parent/guardian to the school office. Students are welcome to bring a lunch from home prior to the school day beginning. Students that forget to bring a lunch will be offered a meal in the cafeteria.

Prairie Freeman
Chief Learning Officer
Breckenridge ISD

post_text:
From Dr. William Paul, BHS Principal
August 18, 2020

Buckaroo Remote Learners:

Tonight please check your school email for an invitation/instructions from your teachers on Google Classroom.

Please make sure you accept the invitation/enroll in the class.

Once you are enrolled, you will need to participate in each class online daily in order to receive credit for attendance that day. As with in-person instruction, assignments will need to be timely in order to receive full credit.

If you have any questions, please visit with your teacher. If you have a difficult time logging in, please send an email directly to your teacher.

Thank You & Go, Bucks!

Brittany Edgar
August 3 at 6:56 AM ·

BUCKAROO football fans!

Today, season tickets go on sale to last years season ticket holders. They go on sale to the public next Wednesday, August 12th.

You can purchase them at BISD Administration Office. Monday-Friday 8am-4pm (closed from 12-1).

They are $30 each.

We ask that you keep in mind there are orders in place that we have to adhere to. DUE TO COVID, things may look and run different this year. Like the stores, we have to follow the rules put in front of us. We will try to run as normal as possible, but things WILL be different this year.

We hope that next year we can return to normal.

We thank you all for supporting BISD and the Breckenridge Buckaroos. 💚

Attention BISD Junior High & High School Students: "Free Online" Summer Coding Camp Offering by Angelo State University

July 20-31, 2020 from 10am-12pm

An online interactive two-week program for junior high and high school students interested in computer programming, coding and creating animations using JavaScript.

Instructors, from Angelo State University’s Computer Science Department, will be available each day via online video conference to assist participants with questions and help them trouble shoot as they learn to solve problems and program independently.

Program: No course fees & Course material available online

Technology required: A personal computer or laptop & Internet access

Cick on this URL to Sign-Up: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSccJZs_gId5fngSjx_5L0QAxh2tJj7jDGZUFb44NoC3QWV1vQ/viewform

A Certificate will be emailed to each participating student.

Additional Information:
https://www.angelo.edu/dept/computer_science/code-camp.php

shared_text:
Patrick Escalon is with Socorro Gallegos Palacios and 4 others.
June 23 at 7:24 PM ·

So proud of this kid, I know he is going to go do great things at the next level! I didn’t expect to get so emotional today but then again these boys are like my own. What I wanted to say about G that my emotions didn’t let me, is the kind of person he is. I had the privilege to coach Gerardo Palacios for 6 years and he is always was very respectful, good natured, and worked hard. He always had a smile on his face no matter the situation and I liked the confidence he brought to the field. I hope you cease this opportunity and go out and make your future happen, it’s there for the taking and I’ll be there to push you when you need it! All those folks that showed up today will be there in your corner, too. Good Luck buddy, love you kid!

shared_text:
Breckenridge FFA
June 23 at 4:23 PM ·

Meet the new addition to the Breckenridge FFA program, Brooke Diaz. Mrs. Diaz graduated from Texas Tech University where she majored in Agriculture Communications. She grew up in Weatherford, Texas exhibiting sheep at every major stock show in the state of Texas. Mrs. Diaz will be starting a wool judging team and taking over the supervision of the sheep/goat projects.

During Mrs. Diaz’s spare time you can find her at stock shows taking pictures as a livestock photographer. She also runs her own photography business on the side. Joining Mrs.Diaz in Breckenridge is her husband, Jacob, and their 5-month-old son, Kash. They also have two corgis named Rose and Lola that will be making the move to Breckenridge!

“I can not wait to meet all of the amazing members
of the Breckenridge FFA Chapter,” said Diaz.

post_text: Thank You, Rachelle!
shared_text:
Rachelle Perry is with Tiffany Nicole and 13 others.
June 6 at 6:43 AM ·

Senior Parents!

I will be taking pictures of your seniors today as they receive their diploma. Because of the circumstance, a lot of family will be distanced away from your seniors as they receive their diploma and I realize how frustrating that is that you wont get to snap an image of that moment. So, because of this, I am going to give everyone of the images I take today to all of you, free of charge. Once they are ready, I will share a link on my personal page with a pin number so that you may download them with full print release and print at your discretion. I will also ask the school to share this link so you might find it on their web and Facebook page. Our family wants to send our condolences to all of you on all of the monumental moments you and your seniors have lost this spring, we are heartbroken for you. We also want to extend our congratulations to your seniors on completion of this phase of their life. We are so proud for you! God bless you and keep you! Go change the world!!!

Rachelle

I will also ask the school to share this link so you might find it on their web and Facebook page. Our family wants to send our condolences to all of you on all of the monumental moments you and your seniors have lost this spring, we are heartbroken for you. We also want to extend our congratulations to your seniors on completion of this phase of their life. We are so proud for you! God bless you and keep you! Go change the world!!!

Rachelle

I need to give a HUGE SHOUT-OUT to Isaak Eutimio & Yuli Ornelas, our yearbook editors. We have worked around the clock for several weeks to get this thing ready for the press. These two young people took the bull by the horns and made it happen. With school never resuming after Spring Break, it was a formidable challenge to say the least, and they rose up and did Buckaroo-Riffic work -- hard and often highly detailed work! Thursday, 04/02/20
Dear Buckaroos & Parents:

The Texas Department of Agriculture has once again changed their rules and are no longer allowing BISD to provide meals during weekends. Therefore, effective immediately, we will only be providing breakfast and lunch, Mondays through Fridays.

Also, effective Monday, April 6, 2020, BISD will reduce the number of feeding sites down to one location. We will serve meals out of the back of the High School Cafeteria. Please refer to the BISD website for the map - this is for DRIVE-THRU meals only. Our service hours will change to 11:00 AM-1:00 PM, Monday through Friday. We apologize for any difficulties this may create, but these changes are outside the control of BISD.

Thank You
Mark Nelson
Director of Child Nutrition
Breckenridge ISD
254-522-9600 EXT 6007

post_text:
3/31/2020
Breckenridge ISD Closed Indefinitely

In response to the county, state, and federal public health recommendations and emergency declarations, Breckenridge ISD will remain closed indefinitely. When public health officials determine that schools can safely reopen, the Breckenridge ISD community will be notified with sufficient time to plan to return to school.

All Breckenridge ISD campuses will continue to provide instruction in the most effective manner possible during this closing. Breakfast and lunch will continue to be served to all school age children 18 years or younger. Please pay attention to the COVID-19 webpage found at www.breckenridgeisd.org for updates.

Thank you for your consideration and patience during this unique and challenging time.

Wash your hands! Practice social distancing! Stay safe and healthy!

Sincerely,
Earl Jarrett
Interim Superintendent

From Mark Nelson, BISD Director of Child Nutrition

Effective: Monday, March 23, 2020

Starting Monday, March 23rd, breakfast will be served from 7:15-8:15 A.M. same as what we have been doing.

Lunch will also be served from 11:30 A.M.-1:00 P.M. We will now, however, include the child's meal for that day as well as their breakfast for the following morning.

Starting Tuesday March 24th, we will only serve once a day, from 11:30 A.M.-1:00 P.M., but we will send home that day's lunch and the next morning’s breakfast.

On Friday, March 27th, and every Friday moving forward, we will send home 6 meals per child: 3 will be for breakfast and 3 will be for lunch. This will provide 2 meals per day per child through Monday morning.

Thank You

post_text:
From Mark Young, Head Boys' Track Coach:

The boys JV and Varsity track team traveled to Hamlin last Friday and had a really good showing and represented Breckenridge on a high level. Last season we had an upper class level of competitors. This year 85% of the team are freshmen and sophomores...but that has not stopped them from competing to the best of their abilities and laying it on the line every track meet and every event. This year and our future is very bright!

JV: (4th place as a team)
200m: 3rd Adrian Ruiz
300h: 2nd Henry Johnson, 4th Kylen Williams
800m: 2nd Chase Lehr
1600m: 1st Chase
4x100: 2nd Kylen, Sean Cooksey, Chicago Harper, Adrian
4x200: 4th Daniel Valdez, Emilio Maya, Sean, Adrian
TJ: 5th Sean
Shot: 6th Isaiah Lehr
Discus: 4th Isaiah, 6th Jerry Lawson

Varsity: (6th as a team)
1600m: 6th Evan Moore
3200m: 3rd Evan
4x200: 6th Julian Eutimio, Tyler Valdez, Ricy Reyes, Colby Stober
4x400: 5th Julian, Tyler, Sean Cooksey, Jaylen Harper
PV: 1st Chris Otts
TJ: 3rd Jaylen

post_text: Congratulations to Kaitlyn Crook. On Wednesday of this week (02/22/20), she earned 1st Place at the Miller Grove UIL Invitational in Prose. The competition was held in Cumby, Texas. Prose is a form of oral interpretation in which the reader performs and tells a story as though they are presenting a scene. Prose speakers must find relevant topics and read pieces of literature relating to certain categories. We would also like to congratulate Jewell Graves for placing 6th overall at this contest. Callie Hodges, BHS Theater Arts Teacher, coaches and manages this program. Great work, Buckaroos!

post_text: For Valentine’s Day at BHS, Student Council and NSHSS made teacher appreciation notes, thanking teachers for what they do for the student body on a daily basis. Vihasi Gandhi, President of NSHSS, and Heer Gandhi, Communication Director of NSHSS, organized Valentines goodies and notes for teachers on Valentine's Day, and ach student from Student Council and NSHSS wrote a notes to all the teachers, adding a little sparkle to their day on the occasion of Valentines. These girls along with some other officers folded about 2000 of these notes into special origami designs to add little twist to the notes. These notes were very well received and exceedingly kind and thoughtful. Thank You!

post_text:
THIS DAY IN HISTORY

On February 13, 1972, the musical “Grease” opened on Broadway for the first time. The musical had run for 3,388 times by 1980 and also had many revivals. There have been only 3 adaptations of the musical, which include 2 movies and one television broadcast. “Grease” won 3 awards and was nominated for 7 others. The musical won the awards for Outstanding Choreography and Outstanding Costume Design at the Drama Desk Awards, as well as a Theatre World Award for the actress Adrienne Barbeau, who played Rizzo. Most people remember the incredibly popular movie by the same name, starring Olivia Newton John and John Travolta that came out in 1978.

By Delaney Bailey, BISD Journalism and Web Media

https://youtu.be/xscJ3C4bUYE

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grease_(musical)

post_text:
ON THIS DAY IN HISTORY

On January 29, 1959, Walt Disney’s film “Sleeping Beauty” was released. The movie was the last of Disney’s fairy tale adaptations until 1989, when “The Little Mermaid” was released. It was the first animated film to be photographed in the Super Technirama 70 widescreen process. “Sleeping Beauty” is based off of the book with the same name, which was written by Charles Perrault. The film had a gross of $51.6 million due to the re-releases and has a total gross of over $623.56 million with the adjusted ticket price for inflation.

By Delaney Bailey, BISD Journalism and Web Media

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sleeping_Beauty_(1959_film)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CfsyUyi_FJM

Sleeping Beauty (1959 film) - Wikipedia
text:
ON THIS DAY IN HISTORY

On January 29, 1959, Walt Disney’s film “Sleeping Beauty” was released. The movie was the last of Disney’s fairy tale adaptations until 1989, when “The Little Mermaid” was released. It was the first animated film to be photographed in the Super Technirama 70 widescreen process. “Sleeping Beauty” is based off of the book with the same name, which was written by Charles Perrault. The film had a gross of $51.6 million due to the re-releases and has a total gross of over $623.56 million with the adjusted ticket price for inflation.

By Delaney Bailey, BISD Journalism and Web Media

post_text:
From Molly Johnson, BISD Chief Learning Officer:

Monday night, 01/20/20, the BISD Board of Trustees approved to change the professional development day from February 14 to February 28. We will have school on February 14 and will follow the regular schedule. February 28 will be a student holiday, and all BISD employees will have a professional development day.

We appreciate everyone's flexibility so that we can provide specific training for teachers that could only be scheduled on the 28th. The district has the opportunity to partner with a team that provides support in school improvement and student success.

Note: This revised calendar is now located on the BISD main website in the drop down menu under calendars and on Buckaroo Mobile Web. Go, Bucks!

THIS DAY IN HISTORY

On January 15, 2001, the website Wikipedia was launched by Jimmy Wales and Larry Sanger. Wikipedia is an online encyclopedia that is maintained by a team of volunteer editors. It’s the largest and most popular reference work on the Internet. The English Wikipedia has over 5 million articles, while the total amount of articles on the website reaches over 40 million. Wikipedia was described as the biggest and possibly best encyclopedia in the world by Time magazine.

By Delaney Bailey, BISD Journalism and Web Media

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia

post_text:
ON THIS DAY IN HISTORY

On January 9, 1959, the western TV series “Rawhide,” starring Clint Eastwood and Eric Fleming, was released. The show ran for 8 seasons on CBS. “Rawhide” is the sixth longest running American western, just after “Wagon Train.” The series has a novel and comic based off of it, which was created by Frank C. Robertson and Dan Spiegle, respectively. “Rawhide” has been nominated for multiple awards and nominations, including Best TV Show from the Golden Globes, and Fictional Television Drama from Western Heritage Awards.

By Delaney Bailey, BISD Journalism and Web Media

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rawhide_(TV_series)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iKikNy4Xo20

post_text: We enjoyed a terrific visit today for Dual Credit American History with BJ Shephard, WWII US Naval Veteran with action in the Pacific Theater, especially Okinawa. He's part of what's called Roll Call, a non-profit veterans' organization out of Fort Worth. Big shout out to BHS Graduate Ricky Stober who set all of this in motion and who has such a heart for military history and veterans. Thanks be to all . . . just a fantastic presentation and dialogue!
